Let me make some historical remarks about my past observations concerning “white saxicolous crustose lichens” found in the coastline of the center of Portugal, close to the city of Peniche, like those in the attached set of photographs.
These lichens all live on rock, have all white thalli and dark apothecia, which are either roundish or more elongated / slit like, sometimes pruinose:

- Arthonia meridionalis Zahlbr.
There are five observations of this species in MO, all by myself. The 1st one is from March, 2017 – observation 270996 and all the remaining are from 2017 and 2018, and all were identified in September, 2018.

- Opegrapha durieui Mont.
There are seven observations of this species in MO, all by myself. The 1st one is from August, 2012, and the others from 2014 to 2018, at the rithm of one (or two) per year. During all this time I searched for a name for the species and succeeded only in September 2018.

- Buellia maritima (A. Massal.) Bagl.
There are nine observations of this species in MO, all by myself. The 1st one is from August, 2011, and the others from 2012 and from 2016 to 2018. All of them except one were found at the same location.

- Dirina massiliensis
There are about twenty observations of this species in MO, all from locations around the city of Peniche, both of the fertile version as well as of the soridiate form. This is a common species here.

- Diplotomma spp.
There are many observations of Diplotomma spp. from the city of Peniche and neighbour locations, incluiding D. alboatrum and D. hedinii.

Cyanescens, however there seems to be differences wich can be seen with the eye. There are no known active Psilocybin sp. in Montana as far as I know. There could possibly be another undocumented species in this area as well. One seems to have a nipple and has the appearance of P. Azurescens but there are obvious differences. There is obvious and rapid bluing with oxidation. These are absolutely active! I will document this one later on.
Lots of these were brought in at NAMA. The snail had first dibs on this one, so I left it in the woods.

Pileus: 100 mm, beige/light brown, fibrillose upturned scales, margin shaggy, fibrillose.
Lamellae: free, close, broad, cream white, subserrulate.
Stipe: 130 × 10 mm, beige/brown, striate, somewhat scabrous above ascending fibrillose annulus, bulbous base.
Odor: not distinctive.
Spore Print: white.
Spores: globose 8 – 10 µm; elliptical 8 -11 × 13 – 17 µm; thick-walled, pore, mono-guttulate with a few being multi-guttulate.
Habitat: solitary, directly under oak, with some beech and ash nearby. The park has a large conifer presence with hardwoods as well.
